        <body>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <head type="title">Autograph Letter, John Ruskin and Margaret Ruskin to John James Ruskin, 15 March 1823</head>
                <div type="section" xml:id="TITLE">
                    <head type="section">Title</head>
                    <p>Untitled.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="GENRE">
                    <head type="section">Genre</head>
                    <p>Autograph letter.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="MAJORMS">
                    <head type="section">Manuscripts</head>
                    <p><orgName corresp="#RUSKINLIBRARYLANCASTER">Ruskin Library</orgName>, Lancaster University, Lancaster, MSL 2/1.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="DATE">
                    <head type="section">Date</head>
                    <p><date when="1823-03-15">15 March 1823</date>. For postal information, 
                        see <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#RFL"><persName corresp="#VAB">Burd</persName>, ed., <title type="book" corresp="#RFL"><hi rend="italic">Ruskin Family Letters</hi></title></ref>, 127.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="COMPPUB">
                    <head type="section">Composition and Publication</head>
                    <p>First published with an omission and editor&#x02bc;s punctuation in 
                        <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#WGCLIFEOFJR1900"><persName corresp="#WGC">Collingwood</persName>, <title type="book" corresp="#WGCLIFEOFJR1900"><hi rend="italic">The Life of John Ruskin</hi></title> (rev. 1900)</ref>, 18&#x2013;19; 
                        and reprinted nearly identically (with a punctuation change) in 
                        <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#JRWORKSLE"><persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>, <title type="book" corresp="#JRWORKSLE"><hi rend="italic">Works</hi></title></ref>, 1:xxvi n. ?.
                        Edited without omission and editorial punctuation, and for the first time along with <persName corresp="#MR">Margaret Ruskin</persName>&#x02bc;s extension 
                        consisting of her own letter to <persName corresp="#JJR">John James</persName>, in 
                        <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#RFL"><persName corresp="#VAB">Burd</persName>, ed., <title type="book" corresp="#RFL"><hi rend="italic">Ruskin Family Letters</hi></title></ref>, 127&#x2013;28. 
                        Partially reproduced in <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#DEARDENRUSKINGALLERIES"><persName corresp="#JSD">James S. Dearden</persName>, <title type="essay" corresp="#DEARDENRUSKINGALLERIES">&#x201C;The <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> Galleries at <orgName corresp="#BEMBRIDGESCHOOL">Bembridge School</orgName>, Isle of Wight&#x201D;</title></ref>, pl. III.</p>
                    
                    <p>Except for the signature, which <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> wrote in pencil and in large capitals, his letter is in <persName corresp="#MR">Margaret</persName>&#x02bc;s hand. 
                        His salutation, letter, and signature are placed first on the sheet, followed by <persName corresp="#MR">Margaret</persName>&#x02bc;s, in which she explains 
                        the circumstances of composition:</p>
                    <floatingText>
                        <body>
                            <div type="letter">
                                <p>Your boy has been very busy scrawling with a pencil on a piece of paper 
                                    which he said was a letter to send to you  I told him I was afraid you would not be able to make it out 
                                    and he said he would read it to me if I would write it to you  the above is exactly word for word 
                                    what he prentended to read from his paper  the signature you will see is his own  sometimes he makes the letters 
                                    much better  he is beginning to copy from his books and will soon learn himself to write I think&#x2014;
                                </p>
                                <p>(<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#RFL"><persName corresp="#VAB">Burd</persName>, ed., <title type="book" corresp="#RFL"><hi rend="italic">Ruskin Family Letters</hi></title></ref>, 128)</p>
                            </div>
                        </body>
                    </floatingText>
                    
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="DISCUSSION">
                    <head type="section">Discussion</head>
                    <p><persName corresp="#WGC">Collingwood</persName> did not include the letter in <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#WGCLIFEOFJR1893"><persName corresp="#WGC">Collingwood</persName>, <title type="book" corresp="#WGCLIFEOFJR1893"><hi rend="italic">The Life and Work of John Ruskin</hi></title> (1893)</ref>, 
                        so it must have lain among &#x201c;the old papers and journals at <placeName corresp="#BRANTWOOD">Brantwood</placeName>&#x201d; and &#x201c;letters hitherto unprinted&#x201d; 
                        that &#x201c;with Mr. <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02bc;s leave, and by permission of Mr. <persName corresp="#GA">George Allen</persName>&#x201d; he was able to supply the &#x201c;new biographical detail&#x201d; 
                        for the revised version of the biography 
                        (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#WGCLIFEOFJR1900"><persName corresp="#WGC">Collingwood</persName>, <title type="book" corresp="#WGCLIFEOFJR1900"><hi rend="italic">The Life of John Ruskin</hi></title> [rev. 1900]</ref>, v).</p>
                </div>
                    
                
            </div>
